- The event that at least one ball is orange (B) is the complement of both balls being blue. The probability both are blue is \(P(\text{both blue}) = \frac{C(2,2)}{C(4,2)} = \frac{1}{6}\), so \(P(B) = 1 - \frac{1}{6} = \frac{5}{6}\).

The conditional probability is \(P(A|B) = \frac{P(A \text{ and } B)}{P(B)}\). Since A implies B (both orange means at least one is orange), \(P(A \text{ and } B) = P(A)\). Thus, \(P(A|B) = \frac{P(A)}{P(B)} = \frac{\frac{1}{6}}{\frac{5}{6}} = \frac{1}{5}\).

Evaluating \(\frac{1}{5}\) to a single numeric value gives 0.2. This is exact and requires no rounding. The answer is a probability and has no unit.

