Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons with a wavelength of 300 nm is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters. Converting 300 nm to meters gives \(\lambda = 300 \times 10^{-9} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\).

First, compute \(h c = (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8) = 1.9878 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{J·m}\).  
Then, \(E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{1.9878 \times 10^{-25}}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}\).  
For one mole, \(E_{\text{mol}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}\).  
Converting to kJ/mol: \(3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol} = 399.0 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).  
Rounding to three significant figures (based on the wavelength of 300 nm having three significant figures) gives 399 kJ/mol.

The typical single-bond energy is given as 400 kJ/mol. Comparing the photon energy (399 kJ/mol) to the bond energy (400 kJ/mol), they are very close, indicating that UV light at 300 nm has sufficient energy to break a typical single bond.

Summary: The final answer is 399
