Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton, which is a spin-1/2 particle, is given by the formula \( S = \sqrt{s(s+1)}  \hbar \), where \( s = \frac{1}{2} \) is the spin quantum number and \( \hbar \) is the reduced Planck's constant.

Substituting \( s = \frac{1}{2} \):  
\[ S = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{1}{2} + 1 \right)}  \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}}  \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}  \hbar = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}  \hbar \]

Using \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J·s} \) and \( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 0.8660254 \):  
\[ S \approx 0.8660254 \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J·s} \approx 9.13286 \times 10^{-35}  \text{J·s} \]

The result is expressed in units of \( 10^{-35}  \text{J·s} \), so the numerical value is approximately 9.13286. Rounded to three significant figures, this is 9.13.

